Fill and boil your #kettle{}. Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C. Pour a good glug of @oil{} onto a #baking tray{} (to completely cover the bottom) and pop onto the top shelf of your oven. Pour the boiling water into a large #saucepan{} on high heat with @salt{0.5%tsp}. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel!). Carefully add the potatoes to the boiling water and cook for ~{5-6%minutes} or until the edges have softened when you poke them with a #knife{}.

Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{}, pop them back into the pan then sprinkle on the @plain flour{8%g} and @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g}. Pop a lid on the pan and give your pan a shake to fluff up the potato and mix in the cheese and flour onto the potatoes. Take your hot baking tray out of your oven, carefully transfer your potatoes onto it in a single layer, turning in the oil. Season the potatoes with @salt{}, then roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{30-35%minutes}, turning halfway through.

Meanwhile, trim the bottom 2cm from the @asparagus{200%g} and pop onto a baking tray. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} then toss to coat. Spread them out in a single layer and set aside. Halve, peel and chop the @echalion shallot{1/2}(peeled and chopped) into small pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(grated). Pick the @sage{1/2}(leaves picked off stalks) leaves off their stalks (4 per person). Sandwich each @British chicken breasts{2} between two pieces of #clingfilm{}, then give it a bash with a #rolling pin{} or the bottom of a saucepan until it's 1-2cm thick all over.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on high heat. Season the chicken with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then place 2 sage leaves on each breast, followed by a rasher of @serrano ham{2%slices}. Once the oil is really hot, carefully lay in the chicken breasts ham side down and cook until browned and crispy, ~{5-6%minutes}, turn down the heat if necessary. Turn and cook for ~{4-5%minutes} on the other side. Once cooked, transfer to a #plate{}, cover with #foil{} and set aside to rest.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle. Keep your pan - you'll need it for the sauce!

~{10-12%minutes} before your roast potatoes are ready, pop the asparagus on the middle shelf of your oven to roast until tender, ~{10-12%minutes}. Put your frying pan back on medium heat and add a drizzle of @oil{}. Add the shallot and stir-fry until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Stir in the garlic and remaining sage leaves and cook, stirring for ~{1%minute}, then add the @cider vinegar{15%ml} and allow it to evaporate, ~{1-2%minutes}. Pour in the @water{100%ml} and @chicken stock powder{1%tsp}, bring to the boil and simmer until reduced by half, ~{2-3%minutes}. Vigorously stir in the @unsalted butter{30%g} until melted, then take it all off the heat.

Taste the sauce and add @?salt{} and @?pepper{} if you feel it needs it.

> TIP: Add a splash of water too if the liquid has evaporated too much and reheat if necessary.

Serve the chicken with the roast potatoes and asparagus alongside. Drizzle over the sauce. Enjoy!